# Real-Time Updates

WebSocket-based real-time synchronization for team collaboration.

## Hard Requirements

- Do: keep real-time event contracts explicit and version-safe.
- Do: handle disconnects with retry/backoff behavior.
- Do not: rely on real-time delivery without fallback sync path.
- Why: resilient real-time systems protect UX under network instability.

## Opinionated Defaults

- Use WebSocket with explicit connection states.
- Use a server-state cache invalidation strategy in response to events.
- Use a dedicated client state store for connection/session state.
- Expose status indicators in UI (connected/reconnecting/disconnected).

## Exceptions

- Low-frequency domains can use polling if websocket complexity is not justified.
- Temporary event gaps are acceptable during phased rollout if background
  reconciliation closes data drift.

## Acceptance Checks

- Connection lifecycle covers initial connect, reconnect, and disconnect states.
- Event handlers map to query invalidation/update behavior.
- Fallback refresh path exists when real-time channel is unavailable.

## Examples

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Connection state handling
const connectionState = {
  connected: false,
  reconnectAttempts: 0,
};

function setConnected(connected: boolean) {
  connectionState.connected = connected;
}
```

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Query invalidation on events
socket.on('item:updated', (event) => {
  invalidateResourceCache(`items:${event.resourceId}`);
});
```
